@node introduction
@title "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction@{ub}

EasyPlayer (EYP) is a user-friendly GUI for shell-based music player
programs such as MPEGA, GMPlay or SIDPLAY. Contrary to most similar
GUIs, it is not tied to one particular player program. EasyPlayer is
*one* GUI for *all* shell-based music players that exist or that are
still to come.

By its concept, EasyPlayer can also be an alternative for AmigaOS 4 or
MorphOS: Although it is 68k, music playing is delegated to the shell
programs, which of course may be PPC-native.
@endnode

@node features
@title "Features"
@{b}Features@{ub}

  * all-in-one: provides one GUI for all shell-based music players.
    Here is a list of the @{"supported music players" link "supported"}

  * extensible: add support for any other shell-based music player in no
    time

  * easy-to-use: intuitive, multithreaded, font-sensitive and resizable
    GUI, online-help and extensive keyboard support

  * playlist: music modules can be comfortably arranged in a playlist
    which can be shuffled, saved, loaded, appended etc.
@endnode

@node supported
@title "Supported music players"
@{b}Supported music players@{ub}

The current version of EasyPlayer comes with predefined interfaces for
eight music player programs covering six different module formats:

  AHX: PlayTHX by Dexter/Abyss, Kyzer/CSG
  Aminet: mus/play/PlayTHX.lha

  MPEG-Audio: MPEGA by Stephane Tavenard
  Aminet: mus/play/MPEGA.lha

  MIDI: GMPlay by Alessandro de Luca and Christian Buchner
  Aminet: mus/midi/GMPlay13.lha

  (Octa-)MED: OctaMEDPlayer by Teijo Kinnunen
  Aminet: mus/play/OctaMEDPlayer7.lha

  ProTracker: ModPlay (from ModUtils) by Ben Hutchings
  Aminet: mus/misc/ModUtils1_27.lha
  and
  EasyMOD by Ralph Debusmann
  Aminet: mus/play/EasyMOD.lha

  SIDPLAY: SIDPLAY by Phill Wooller
  Aminet: mus/play/sidplay.lha
  and (less CPU-intensive, using "playsid.library")
  Clips by Dave Dustin
  Aminet: mus/play/Clips.lha
@endnode

@node requirements
@title "Requirements"
@{b}Requirements@{ub}

* an Amiga running AmigaOS 2.04 (V37) or higher

* reqtools.library V38 or higher

* amigaguide.library V34 or higher (optional)

* some (shell-based) music player programs
@endnode

@node install
@title "Installation"
@{b}Installation@{ub}

1. Copy the "EasyPlayer"-directory to some place on your harddisk.

2. Define @{"interfaces" link "interfaces"} for your shell-based music
player programs.

Since EasyPlayer comes with a predefined set of interfaces for the for
many common shell-based music players, step 2 is usually very easy: just
tell EasyPlayer where the respective player can be found on your
harddisk and off you go.
@endnode

@node windows
@title "Windows"
@{b}Windows@{ub}

EasyPlayer makes use of four windows: 

  * @{"Playlist" link "playlist"}: This is the main window. It contains the playlist (= a
    list of modules) and two rows of buttons.

  * @{"Preferences" link "preferences"}: Here you can customize EasyPlayer's overall
    behaviour.

  * @{"Interfaces" link "interfaces"}: the list of interfaces. Here you can add new interfaces,
    edit them, delete them etc.

  * @{"Interface definition" link "interface"}: Here you edit an interface. Since EasyPlayer
    is multithreaded, an arbitrary number of interface-windows can be
    open in parallel.
@endnode

@node playlist
@title "Playlist"
@{b}Playlist@{ub}

The Playlist-window contains the playlist (= list of modules) and two
rows of buttons.

The first row of buttons is called "playlist buttons" and is used to
manipulate the playlist. From left to right, the buttons' functions and
keyboard shortcuts are:

  function                           shortcut

  add module(s)                      "+"
  remove module                      Del or "-"
  move module to top                 "f"
  move module up                     "p"
  move module down                   "d"
  move module to bottom              "l"
  sort modules a-z                   "a"
  sort modules z-a                   "z"
  shuffle modules                    "s"

The second row of buttons is called "tapedeck buttons" and is used to
control music playback (= the respective player program). From left to
right, the buttons' functions and keyboard shortcuts are:

  function                           shortcut

  play previous module               Shift + Cursor left
  add and play module(s)             Shift + Return
  set subsong number                 Cursor left and right
  play next module                   Shift + Cursor right
  stop module                        Space
  eject module(s)                    Tab

Here are some more shortcuts:

  function                           shortcut

  go to previous module              Cursor up
  go to next module                  Cursor down
  go to top of the list              Alt + Cursor up
  go to bottom of the list           Alt + Cursor down
  go to module currently played      "g"
  info about module currently played "i"
  play module                        Return or Mouse double click
  toggle low-pass filter             "t"

--

Notes:

  * In the "add module" filerequester, enter the asterisk ("*")
    as the filename to add 1) all files from the current directory,
    and 2) all files from its subdirectories. Their relative path
    (relative to the current directory) is added and sorted
    alphabetically.

  * Use the menu items "Open", "Append" and "Save As" in the
    "Project"-pulldown menu to open, append and save playlists.

  * Use the "Snapshot"-menu item to snapshot the Playlist-window's
    position and size. This information is then saved to the preferences
    file.

  * Closing the window or pressing Esc quits.

  * Press HELP for the online-help.
@endnode

@node preferences
@title "Preferences"
@{b}Preferences@{ub}

Here you can customize EasyPlayer's overall behaviour:

  Module path
    Default module path. Press "1" to open the corresponding
    filerequester (same as the button to the right of the text field)
    via keyboard.

  Playlist path
    Default playlist path. Press "2" to open the corresponding
    filerequester (same as the button to the right of the text field)
    via keyboard.

  Be quiet
    If enabled, EasyPlayer redirects the music player's output to NIL:,
    regardless of the "Console"-setting in the corresponding
    interface-definition. The effect is that no console windows pop up
    anymore.

  Timeout
    Sets the timeout for playing modules (in seconds). 0 means no
    timeout. If the timeout is reached, EasyPlayer goes on to play the
    next module on the playlist (if there is a next module), or stops
    (if there is no next module).

--

Notes:

  * Use the menu items "Open" and "Save As" in the
    "Preferences"-pulldown menu to open and save playlists.

  * The default preferences filename is "EYP.prefs" in "PROGDIR:" (= the
    directory from which EasyPlayer has been launched).

  * All changes in the preferences are automatically "Use"d. "Cancel"
    undos the changes made.

  * Closing the window or pressing Esc "Use"s the preferences.

  * Press HELP for the online-help.
@endnode

@node interfaces
@title "Interfaces"
@{b}Interfaces@{ub}

"Interfaces" define two things:

  1. How a music module of a certain kind can be recognized (e.g.
     MP3-files have the suffix ".mp3")

  2. Which music player shall be invoked to play this module.

Interfaces can be active or non-active. The name of a non-active
interface is preceded by a star "*". Non-active interfaces do not take
part in module recognition.

One interface can be a fallback interface. The name of a fallback
interface is preceded by an exclamation mark "!". The fallback
interface's player is invoked if no interface could recognize the music
module. This is more or less a trick useful e.g. when accessing a
MP3-CD-ROM created on a Windows-machine: here, the filenames of the MP3s
are often truncated. If MP3-module recognition depends on the filename
suffix (e.g. ".mp3") and the filename suffix is truncated, the MP3-file
cannot be recognized. The solution is to declare the MPEGA-interface as
a fallback interface. Then, MPEGA is invoked on all unrecognized files,
including MP3s with truncated filenames. An arbitrary number of
interfaces may be declared to be a fallback interface, but only one of
them (the topmost in the list of interfaces) is *the* fallback
interface.

In the interfaces window ("EYP ints") you can administrate the
interfaces. The buttons in the row directly below the list of interfaces
have the following functions:

  New: add a new interface
  Edit: edit an interface
  Copy: duplicate an interface
  *: (in-)activate interface
  !: (un-)declare as fallback interface
  Del: delete interface
  Clear: delete all interfaces

The buttons to the right of the list of interfaces do this:

  First: move interface to top
  Up: move interface up
  Down: move interface down
  Last: move interface to bottom
  a-z: sort interfaces in ascending order
  z-a: sort interfaces in descending order

Here are some more shortcuts:

  function                           shortcut

  go to previous interface           Cursor up
  go to next interface               Cursor down
  go to top of the list              Alt + Cursor up
  go to bottom of the list           Alt + Cursor down
  go to interface currently playing  g
  edit interface                     Return or Mouse double click

--

Notes:

  * Use the menu items "Open", "Append" and "Save As" in the
    "Interfaces"-pulldown menu to open and save playlists.

  * The default interfaces filename is "EYP.ints" in "PROGDIR:" (= the
    directory from which EasyPlayer has been launched).

  * The order of the list of interfaces is crucial: In search of an
    interface for a music module the list is traversed from top to
    bottom. If interfaces A and B both could recognize a module, and A
    comes before B in the list of interfaces, A will be used (and not
    B).

  * All changes in the interface list are automatically "Use"d. "Cancel"
    undos the changes made.

  * Closing the window or pressing Esc "Use"s the interfaces.

  * Press HELP for the online-help.
@endnode

@node interface
@title "Interface definition"
@{b}Interface definition@{ub}

Each interface definition is made up of information how to recognize a
module of a certain kind ("Recognition") and information how to invoke
the corresponding music player program ("Invocation"). This definition can
be edited in the interface definition-window.

Notice that to make an interface work, just the following fields must be
filled in: (1) The path to the player program in the "Path"-gadget. (2)
The module-argument "%m" into the "Args"-gadget. (3) EasyPlayer needs to
know how to recognize the modules, either by their header ("Header" and
"Offset") or by their filename ("Pattern"). (1) and (2) are to be set in
the "Invocation"-tab, and (3) in the "Recognition"-tab of the interface
definition.

Here are some @{"example interface definitions" link "examples"}.

Invocation

    Name
      Name of the interface. A star "*" at the beginning of an interface
      name declares it inactive. An exclamation mark "!" at the
      beginning of an interface name declares that it is a fallback
      interface.

    Path
      Full path of the music player program. The program should be
      shell-based and stop after being sent a "CTRL_C"-signal. Press "1"
      to open the corresponding filerequester (same as the button to the
      right of the text field) via keyboard.

    Args
      The shell-arguments of the music player program. This includes the
      module-argument and the subsong-argument, both of which can be given
      using format signs: %m is the placeholder for the module-argument
      and %s the placeholder for the subsong-argument. The
      module-argument must be included. The subsong-argument must only
      be included if the interface supports subsongs. Usually, just setting
      Args to "%m" (the module-argument enclosed in quotes) does the trick,
      i.e. is the minimal definition.

    Help arg
      Help argument and console definition. Hints:
        * Use the "WAIT"-option to keep the console from closing right
          after it has been opened.

        * "Control" + "Backslash" can be used to close console windows.

        * Enclose the console definition in quotes if its window title
          contains spaces.

        * A minimal but sensible definition for "Help arg" goes like
          this:
          >CON://///WAIT.

        * A ">" must be placed in front of the "Help arg"-console
          definition.
        
    Console
      Console definition when the player program is launched to play a
      module. There are four differences to note compared to "Help arg"-
      console definition:
        * The "WAIT"-option must not be used.

        * The console definition must not be enclosed in quotes.

        * Minimal definition: CON: for a console, NIL: for no output.

        * Do not place a ">" in front of the "Console" definition.

    Force filter off
      If checked, EasyPlayer will turn off the filter a couple of times
      in a second while playing a module.

Recognition

    Header
      A string representing the music module header of the format
    Offset
      Offset of the header (in bytes from begin of module). If no header
      is given, the offset isn't taken into account.

    Pattern
      AmigaDOS-pattern to recognize modules of this format. Might come
      in useful if you want to recognize XPK- or PowerPacker-crunched
      modules.

    Subsong support
      Check if the format supports subsongs

    Def song offset
      Offset of default subsong ordinal in module (in bytes from begin
      of module)
    Len
      Length of default subsong ordinal (1-4 bytes, 0 means that there
      is no default subsong ordinal to be found in the module)
    Add to value
      Add a number to the dafault song value. Some module formats count
      their subsongs from 0 to N-1 instead of from 1 to N. Add 1 in
      these cases. If modules of the format to be defined do not have a
      default song, also add 1. (e.g. (Octa)MED, see also @{"examples" link "examples"}).

    Num songs offset
      Offset of the number of subsongs ordinal (in bytes from begin of
      module)
    Len
      Length of number of subsongs ordinal (1-4 bytes, 0 means that
      there is no number of subsongs ordinal to be found in the module)
    Add to value
      Add a number to the value read for the number of songs in the
      module. (Octa)MED-modules for example state N-1 as the number of
      songs although there are N subsongs. Add 1 in this case (see also
      @{"examples" link "examples"}).

--

Notes

  * Any number of interfaces can be edited in parallel.

  * All changes in an interface definition are automatically "Use"d.
    "Cancel" undos the changes made.

  * Closing the window or pressing Esc "Use"s the interface definition.

  * Press HELP for the online-help.

  * Use the debug mode (can be toggled on and off using the Project-menu
    item) to show the composed command including its arguments.

  * A few older player programs (mostly those with <OS 2-argument
    handling) do not support quoted filenames. Do not enclose the
    module-argument into quotes in this case: write %m instead of "%m".

  * Here is the full story of how recognition proceeds. Only active
    interfaces take part in the recognition process. EasyPlayer
    traverses the list of *active* interfaces from top to bottom in
    order to recognize a module. The first interface which recognizes
    the module is invoked on the module. If no interface recognizes the
    module, the first fallback interface (marked by a "!") is invoked.
    If there is no fallback interface in the list of interfaces, nothing
    is invoked. Use the debug mode to indicate whether a module has been
    properly recognized or whether it has not been recognized and the
    fallback interface invoked.
@endnode

@node examples
@title "Examples"
@{b}Examples@{ub}

This section is about some example interface definitions that shall serve
as a kind of tutorial. I will define three interfaces and comment on some
definitions:

  @{b}MPEGA@{ub}

    Invocation
      Name: MPEGA
      Path: PATH_TO_MPEGA:MPEGA
      Args: -n -i "%m"
        -n means "no frame counter" and -i "display TAG infos", "%m" is
        the module-argument
      Help arg: >"CON:0/0/500/500/EYP MPEGA help/CLOSE/WAIT"
        This defines a console window at the top left corner of the screen
        with width 500 and height 500 pixels, and to be equipped with a
        close-gadget ("CLOSE"-option).
      Console: CON:0/0/400/200/EYP MPEGA console/CLOSE
      Force filter off: Unchecked

    Recognition
      Header: ID3
        Some MP3s bear this header at offset 0.
      Offset: 0
      Pattern: (#?.mp2|#?.mp3)
        If the header could not be matched, match the MP2/MP3's
        filename with either #?.mp2 or #?.mp3.
      Subsong support: Unchecked

  @{b}SIDPLAY@{ub}

    Invocation
      Name: SIDPLAY
      Path: PATH_TO_SIDPLAY:SIDPLAY
      Args: "%m" -o%s
        "%m" is the module-argument, the subsong-argument %s is preceded
        by -o.
      Help arg: >"CON:0/0/500/300/EYP SIDPLAY help/CLOSE/WAIT"
      Console: CON:0/0/500/200/EYP SIDPLAY console/CLOSE
      Force filter off: Unchecked
    Recognition
      Header: PSID
        This is the SIDPLAY-module file header.
      Offset: 0
      Pattern: (none)
      Subsongs: Checked
      Def song offset: 16
        The default song ordinal can be found at offset 16...
      Len: 2
        ... and is 2 bytes long.
      Add to value: 0
      Num songs offset: 14
        The number of songs within a SIDPLAY-module can be
        found at offset 14 ...
      Len: 2
        ... and is 2 bytes long, too.
      Add to value: 0

  @{b}OctaMEDPlayer@{ub}

    Invocation
      Name: OctaMEDPlayer
      Path: PATH_TO_OctaMEDPlayer:OctaMEDPlayer
      Args: "%m" %s
        "%m" is the module-argument, %s the subsong-argument
        (OctaMEDPlayer expects the song number right after the
        module-argument).
      Help arg: ? >"CON:0/0/500/200/EYP OctaMEDPlayer help/CLOSE/WAIT"
      Console: KCON:0/0/400/100/EYP OctaMEDPlayer console/CLOSE
      Force filter off: Unchecked
    Recognition
      Header: MMD
      Offset: 0
      Pattern: (none)
      Subsongs: Checked
      Def song offset: 0
      Len: 0
        No default song offset ordinal
      Add to value: 1
      Num songs offset: 50
        The number of songs within a OctaMED-module can be found at offset
        50 ...
      Len: 2
        ... and is 2 bytes long.
      Add to value: 1
@endnode

@node shell
@title "Shell support"
@{b}Shell support@{ub}

Here is EasyPlayer's commandline template:

  MOD=MODULE/M,PLST=PLAYLIST

  MOD=MODULE
    Pass a list of modules to EasyPlayer upon shell-startup. Here is an
    example:
      EYP MOD=mod.monotonika MOD=Lightforce.mid

    The list may also contain patterns representing a set of modules:
      EYP MOD=mod.#? MOD=#?.mp3

    The MOD (= MODULE)-keyword may also be dropped:
      EYP mod.monotonika Lightforce.mid
      EYP mod.#? #?.mp3

  PLST=PLAYLIST
    Pass a playlist to EasyPlayer upon shell-startup. For example:
      EYP PLST=C64Music
    The PLST(= PLAYLIST)-keyword may not be dropped.

It is possible to pass over to EasyPlayer both a list of modules and a
playlist. In this case, the playlist will be appended to the list of
modules.
@endnode

@node workbench
@title "Workbench support"
@{b}Workbench support@{ub}

EasyPlayer supports multiple Workbench-arguments (i.e. modules) and can
be used as the default tool for music modules.

When EasyPlayer has been started from Workbench, the Playlist-window
becomes an AppWindow: then you can add modules to the playlist by
dropping the corresponding Workbench-icons on the Playlist-window.
@endnode

